# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidimicrobiia] The ***Acidimicrobiia*** are a class of Actinomycetota, in which three families, eight genera, and nine species have been described, *Acidimicrobium ferrooxidans* is the type species of the order.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidimicrobiia] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteria] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteriia] The "**Acidobacteriia**" is a class of Acidobacteriota.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidobacteriia] Numbered orders do not yet have any cultured representatives.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Acidulidesulfobacteriota are ecologically significant in biogeochemical cycling, especially with respect to sulfur and iron.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Their genomes show evidence of interaction with viruses, which can influence host metabolic functions including folate biosynthesis and sulfur pathways.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] The **Actinomycetota** (previously known as **"Actinobacteria"**) are a diverse phylum of Gram-positive bacteria with high guanine-cytosine content (GC content or G+C content).
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] They are of great importance to land flora because of their contributions to soil systems.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] In soil, they help decompose organic matter of dead organisms so the molecules can be taken up anew by plants.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] While this role is also played by fungi, actinomycetota are much smaller and likely do not occupy the same ecological niche.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] In this role, the colonies often grow extensive mycelia, as fungi do, and the name of an important order of the phylum, Actinomycetales (the actinomycetes), reflects that they were long believed to be fungi.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] Some soil actinomycetota (such as *Frankia*) live symbiotically with the plants whose roots pervade the soil, fixing nitrogen for the plants in exchange for access to some of the plant's saccharides.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] Other species, such as many members of the genus *Mycobacterium*, are important pathogens.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] Beyond the great interest in Actinomycetota for their soil role, much is yet to be learned about them.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] Although currently understood primarily as soil bacteria, they might be more abundant in fresh waters.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] Actinomycetota is one of the dominant bacterial phyla and contains one of the largest of bacterial genera: *Streptomyces*.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] *Streptomyces* and other actinomycetota are major contributors to biological buffering of soils.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] They are also the source of many antibiotics.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] Bacteria of the Actinomycetota genus *Bifidobacterium* are the most common in the microbiome of human infants.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] Although adults have fewer bifidobacteria, intestinal bifidobacteria help maintain the mucosal barrier and reduce lipopolysaccharides in the intestine.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] Although some of the largest and most complex bacterial cells belong to the Actinomycetota, the group of marine Actinomarinales has been described as possessing the smallest free-living prokaryotic cells.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] Some Siberian or Antarctic biofilms of these bacteria are said to have the longest lifespan of any organism on Earth, frozen in permafrost at around half a million years ago.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] Most actinomycetota of medical or economic significance are in class Actinomycetia, and belong to the order Actinomycetales.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] While many of these cause disease in humans, *Streptomyces* is notable as a source of antibiotics.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] Of those actinomycetota not in the Actinomycetales, *Gardnerella* is one of the most researched.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] Classification of *Gardnerella* is controversial, and MeSH catalogues it as both a Gram-positive and Gram-negative organism.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] Actinomycetota-derived antibiotics that are important in medicine include aminoglycosides, anthracyclines, chloramphenicol, macrolides, tetracyclines, etc.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] Actinomycetota have high guanine and cytosine content in their DNA.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] The GC content of actinomycetota can be as high as 70%, though some may have a low GC content.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinobacteria] Analysis of glutamine synthetase sequence has been suggested for phylogenetic analysis of the Actinomycetota.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinomycetales] Actinomycetales have 2 main forms of reproduction: spore formation and hyphae fragmentation.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinomycetales] During reproduction, Actinomycetales can form conidiophores, sporangiospores, and oidiospores.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinomycetales] In reproducing through hyphae fragmentation, the hyphae formed by Actinomycetales can be a fifth to half the size of fungal hyphae, and bear long spore chains.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinomycetales] Actinomycetales can be found mostly in soil and decaying organic matter, as well as in living organisms such as humans and animals.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinomycetales] They form symbiotic nitrogen fixing associations with over 200 species of plants, and can also serve as growth promoting or biocontrol agents, or cause disease in some species of plants.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinomycetales] Actinomycetales can be found in the human urogenital tract as well as in the digestive system including the mouth, throat, and gastrointestinal tract in the form of Helicobacter without causing disease in the host.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinomycetales] They also have wide medicinal and botanical applications, and are used as a source of many antibiotics and pesticides.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinomycetales] Many species of Actinomycetes produce antimicrobial compounds under certain conditions and growth media.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinomycetales] Streptomycin, actinomycin, and streptothricin are all medically important antibiotics isolated from Actinomycetes bacteria.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/actinomycetales] Almost two-thirds of the natural antimicrobial drug compounds used currently are produced by different species of Actinomycetes.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology] The manual was published subsequent to ***Bergey's Manual of Determinative Bacteriology***, though the latter is still published as a guide for identifying unknown bacteria.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology] First published in 1923 by David Hendricks Bergey, it is used to classify bacteria based on their structural and functional attributes by arranging them into specific familial orders.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology] However, this process has become more empirical in recent years.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology] The ***Taxonomic Outline of Bacteria and Archaea*** is a derived publication indexing taxon names from version two of the manual.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology] It used to be available for free from the Bergey's manual trust website until September 2018.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology] Michigan State University provides an alternative version that indexes NamesforLife records.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology] The five-volume BMSB is officially replaced by ***Bergey's Manual of Systematics of Archaea and Bacteria*** (BMSAB), a continuously-updated online book, since 2015.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology] The change in volume set to "*Systematic Bacteriology*" came in a new contract in 1980, whereupon the new style included "relationships between organisms" and had "expanded scope" overall.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology] This new style was picked up for a four-volume set that first began publishing in 1984.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology] The current volumes differ drastically from previous volumes in that many higher taxa are not defined in terms of phenotype, but solely on 16S phylogeny, as is the case of the classes within Proteobacteria.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology] Bergey's Manual Trust was established in 1936 to sustain the publication of *Bergey's Manual of Determinative Bacteriology* and supplementary reference works.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology] The Trust also recognizes individuals who have made outstanding contributions to bacterial taxonomy by presentation of the Bergey Award and Bergey Medal, jointly supported by funds from the Trust and from Springer, the publishers of the Manual.
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology] Bergey's Manual Trust and John Wiley & Sons, Inc. co-publish the online encyclopedia *Bergey's Manual of Systematics of Archaea and Bacteria* (BMSAB).
[src:bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology/bergey-s-manual-of-systematic-bacteriology] On 2019, the Trust decided to include phylogenomic in the BMSAB using the classification provided by the Genome Taxonomy Database (GTDB).
